%N A390645 Triangle read by rows: T(n,r) is maximal such that there exists a family F of subsets of {1,...,n} of size T(n,r) such that the intersection of no two sets in F has r elements.
%C A390645 For fixed r and n(r) sufficiently large Frankl and Füredi proved that T(n,r) is maximized by taking F such that for all A in F: |A| > (n+r)/2 or |A| < r when n+r is odd, and|A\{1}| >= (n+r)/2 or |A| < r when n+r is even.
%C A390645 Earlier Frankl proved that for r=1 and all n>3.
%H A390645 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/703">Problem #703</a>, Erdős Problems.
%H A390645 Péter Frankl, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/bf01896201">An intersection problem for finite sets</a>, Acta Math. Acad. Sci. Hungar. (1977), 371-373.
%H A390645 Péter Frankl and Zoltån Füredi, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0097-3165(84)90008-6">On hypergraphs without two edges intersecting in a given number of vertices</a>, J. Combin. Theory Ser. A (1984), 230-236.
%H A390645 Péter Frankl and Vojtěch Rödl, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0002-9947-1987-0871675-6">Forbidden intersections</a>, Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. (1987), 259-286.
%F A390645 T(n,0) = 2^(n-1).
%F A390645 T(n,1) = A045621(n+1) + 1 for n > 3.
%F A390645 T(n,n) = 2^n.
%F A390645 T(n,n-1) = 2^n - 1.
%F A390645 T(n,n-2) = A000295(n) for n > 2.
%e A390645 The triangle begins:
%e A390645   1,
%e A390645   1,  2,
%e A390645   2,  3,  4,
%e A390645   4,  4,  7,  8,
%e A390645   8,  6,  11, 15, 16,
%e A390645   16, 11, 16, 26, 31, 32,
%e A390645   32, 23, 22, 42, 57, 63,  64,
%e A390645   64, 45, 37, 64, 99, 120, 127, 128...
%t A390645 T[n_,r_]:= Length[FindClique[RelationGraph[DigitSum[BitAnd[#1,#2],2]!=r&,Range[2^n]]][[1]]];
